### Description

Right now, when you try to bind to `input` of *host directive* using `host`, it will not work. It is possible to use `output` of *host directive* using `host`. It would be awesome if this also works with `input` and it would be totally awesome if it would work together with `typeCheckHostBindings`. Right now you will receive error `Can't bind to 'in' since it isn't a known property of 'home-view'.` But this is not working either way, so its no big problem, that error.

**test.directive.ts**
```ts
/**
 * Test directive
 */
@Directive(
{
    selector: '[test]',
})
export class TestDirective
{
    public in: InputSignal<string|undefined> = input<string|undefined>();

    constructor()
    {
        effect(() =>
        {
            console.log(this.in());
        });
    }
}
```

**home.component.ts**
```ts
/**
 * Home component
 */
@Component(
{
    selector: 'home-view',
    templateUrl: 'home.component.html',
    host:
    {
        '[in]': 'inVal()',
    },
    hostDirectives:
    [
        {
            directive: TestDirective,
            inputs: ['in'],
        },
    ],
    changeDetection: ChangeDetectionStrategy.OnPush
})
@ComponentRedirectRoute('', 'home')
@ComponentRoute({path: 'home'})
@WithScrollableCssClass()
export class HomeComponent
{
    public inVal: Signal<string> = signal('test');
}
```

You would expect that code above will work as it is working for outputs, but value in `input` is never set.

**Minimal reproduction:**

- `git clone https://github.com/kukjevov/ng-universal-demo.git demo`
- `cd demo`
- `git checkout bug/2.0`
- `npm install`
- change value of `typeCheckHostBindings` in `tsconfig.json` to `false`
- `npm start`
- open `https://localhost:8888/` and you will see that there is console log `undefined`

